the Third Reich through the experiences of women of different ages—Marianne Rosenbaum's Peppermint Peace, Helma Sanders-Brahms's Germany, Pale Mother, Jutta Brückner's Hunger Years, Margarethe von Trotta's Marianne and Juliane, and Jeanine Meerapfel's Malou. By juxtaposing these films with the accepted theories on German culture, Linville offers a fresh appraisal not only of the films' importance but especially of their challenge to misogynist interpretations of the German failure to grieve for the horrors of its Nazi past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aGuilt. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszGermanyxPsychological aspects. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directorszGermany. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74696140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799721423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799721/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK